have used Web Fonts, which is awesome to see.
For those of you who have used Web Fonts,

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:10.331
hopefully this presentation gives you a little
bit more detail into what Google is doing

00:01:10.331 --> 00:01:14.600
in this space. For those of you who haven't
used Web Fonts, it will be a pleasure to introduce

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:20.020
you to the topic.
Here is a quick overview of what we will be

00:01:20.020 --> 00:01:24.619
talking about in the next 45 minutes. We will
start with a Web Fonts crash course. We are

00:01:24.619 --> 00:01:28.880
going to describe what Web Fonts are, why
you should potentially be excited about Web

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:31.860
Fonts, and why Google is excited about Web
Fonts.

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:38.310
We will then go into Google Web Fonts' overview,
which is Google's offering in this space.

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:44.671
It is available at google.com/webfonts. It
was launched last year one year ago at Google

00:01:44.671 --> 00:01:48.310
I/O.
Next we are going to talk about some interesting

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:53.390
trends we have been seeing with Web font adoption.
Finally, we are going to talk about what the

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:58.330
Web Fonts teams at Google has been up to,
specifically three areas: Our efforts to increase

00:01:58.330 --> 00:02:06.380
the fonts we offer as well as to change how
users surf and choose and select their Web

00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:10.399
Fonts. Second, we are going to talk about
our efforts to make Web Fonts faster and more

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:14.140
efficient.
And, third, our efforts to incorporate Google

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:17.910
Web Fonts into all the tools that you use
every day in your everyday workflows.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:26.720
Let's jump into the crash course. Until recently,
the state of web typography has resembled

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:34.440
a barren desert. When you are writing your
CSS and you decided you would like to style

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:39.600
a bit of text on your page. You have been
constrained to use the font families that

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:44.160
are installed on Microsoft Windows, which
is the prevalent operating system. This means

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:48.980
we've seen a lot of Arial, Courier, Georgia,
Times, Verdana. We know these font families

00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:54.530
very well because they are really the only
ones you can use as true, selectable Web-safe

00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:58.400
fonts.
Now, if you compare the visual diversity of

00:02:58.400 --> 00:03:02.510
the average Web site to the visual diversity
of the average magazine, for example, the

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:07.070
difference is quite staggering. What you will
find in the print world is that fonts are

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:11.710
used to convey much more subtle ideas and
the variation of fonts in the print world

00:03:11.710 --> 00:03:16.540
is staggering relative to the Web.
So we think this limitation is unfortunate

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:23.050
to say the least and it is rather artificial.
But we've seen nice fonts on the Web before.

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:27.890
So there's obviously a way to do it. But we
do consider these things the ugly work-arounds.

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:33.990
You embed text in images which, basically,
means that the content is not semantic anymore.

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:38.260
You are going to have to rely on alt tags,
which not everyone uses. And it doesn't seem

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:41.220
-- it is an abstraction of the content that
you would like to embed in your page. It is

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:45.830
not actually the content.
And if you embed text in images, your text

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:51.070
isn't selectable so it is not copy and pasteable.
And it is not zoomable. So perhaps your users

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:57.460
prefer to see the text slightly larger sizes.
And if you increase the page size in your

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:02.690
browser and you have text in image, it quickly
degrades in quality. If it is actually a real

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:05.210
font, it looks really nice and the curbs are
maintained.

00:04:05.210 --> 00:04:10.430
And there is another way to do it. You can
use what's called a Flash replacement technique

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:17.190
which, basically, renders an Adobe Flash object
on top of the object for your text and that

00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:22.729
Adobe Flash object contains your font file
but it requires a plug-in. And there is a

00:04:22.729 --> 00:04:29.039
slight flash of unstyled text before the Adobe
Flash loads on top of the unstyled text. And

00:04:29.039 --> 00:04:35.710
the selection field is a bit odd. You can
tell it is not HTML. So it is obvious the

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:40.360
Web needed a better way to use and select
fonts.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:45.349
So the solution is Web Fonts. Web Fonts free
of you of the constraint. You no longer need

00:04:45.349 --> 00:04:49.870
to refer to fonts that are installed on a
user's local machine when you are writing

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:55.370
your CSS stack. Instead, you can refer to
any font because, theoretically, any font

00:04:55.370 --> 00:05:01.240
can be served via HTTP request.
So there's other benefits to Web Fonts. Web

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:06.560
Fonts are semantic. What you type, what you
mark up into your pages is what you mean to

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:11.849
mark up. It is not an abstraction of the content.
And because it is more semantic, there's a

00:05:11.849 --> 00:05:17.060
load of other benefits. It is more translatable
into other languages. It is more accessible

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:22.240
to screen readers. It is zoomable. And as
Raph is going to talk about just a little

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:27.189
bit later, Web Fonts can be super efficient
as well.

00:05:27.189 --> 00:05:32.240
Google loves Web Fonts. Web Fonts not only
make the Web more expressive, more semantic,

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:37.360
more accessible, more translatable, but they
also make it more searchable. And we think

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:42.350
Web Fonts is a win for everybody involved.
It is a win for you, the webmasters and content

00:05:42.350 --> 00:05:47.319
creators of the Internet, because you have
access to a much wider font selection to express

00:05:47.319 --> 00:05:50.560
yourselves and you can make your pages more
semantic and accessible.

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:54.890
It's a win for your users because they can
increase font size. They can copy and paste.

00:05:54.890 --> 00:05:59.710
They can translate it into other languages.
And it is a win for Google users because Google

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:04.280
Search is going to become better. Google wants
Web Fonts to be ubiquitous, and that's part

00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:11.240
of the reason why we launched Google Web Fonts
last year at Google I/O.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:17.620
Web Fonts is not cutting edge HTML5 stuff.
It is actually supported in 98% of browsers

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:23.159
right now. Now, support for Web Fonts actually
goes back to the days of IE4. It has been

00:06:23.159 --> 00:06:27.650
on and off in the early browsers. Back then
it wasn't a reliable choice for webmasters

00:06:27.650 --> 00:06:31.800
because not all browsers supported it. When
a browser didn't support Web Fonts, it would

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.499
have a very bad failure case where the font
would just not -- your text would just not

00:06:35.499 --> 00:06:39.319
display.
But recently in the last two years, browsers

00:06:39.319 --> 00:06:45.229
started supporting Web Fonts, which means
right now they are a great choice for production

00:06:45.229 --> 00:06:51.801
applications in Web sites.
When I say "the browsers support Web Fonts,"

00:06:51.801 --> 00:06:57.520
what I'm referring to specifically is the
@font-face CSS rule. This is the underlying

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:02.249
technology behind Google Web Fonts.
What we are showing on screen here is what's

00:07:02.249 --> 00:07:07.680
called the bullet-proof syntax which is, basically,
the CSS you would use if you wanted to host

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:12.669
a font yourself and serve it as a Web font.
And so let's go through it one by one. First

00:07:12.669 --> 00:07:17.199
we are defining the font family. In this case,
Droid Sans. And there is the font style and

00:07:17.199 --> 00:07:21.850
the font weight. Then we get to the point
where we source it. It can either be a URL,

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:27.169
which is a remote source or a local source.
There are various formats.

00:07:27.169 --> 00:07:31.409
Now, it might look like there's some typos
in this snippet, but it ends up this is -- everything

00:07:31.409 --> 00:07:39.099
in here is intentional. Certain browsers ignore
certain bits of the snippet. And if you do

00:07:39.099 --> 00:07:43.749
it exactly like this, you can have reasonable
confidence that your font will work across

00:07:43.749 --> 00:07:49.680
browsers and platforms. But there are some
downsides of using font-face directly. As

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:54.400
we saw, there is a lot of font file formats
that are used. And this is because different

00:07:54.400 --> 00:08:00.560
browsers require different font formats.
And if you'd like to host a font yourself,

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:04.809
you're going to have to, basically, take that
font file and convert it into SVG and WOFF

00:08:04.809 --> 00:08:08.569
and EOT.
The second is that you will need to find a

00:08:08.569 --> 00:08:13.260
host for these font files and one you can
trust because if it breaks, your Web page

00:08:13.260 --> 00:08:17.550
is going to look completely different. Now,
for many of you who have a Web host already

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:21.779
set up, this is probably not a huge requirement.
But think about the bloggers, the mom-and-pop

00:08:21.779 --> 00:08:26.350
bloggers out there which don't necessarily
have ready access to a Web host. This could

00:08:26.350 --> 00:08:31.729
actually be a huge deterrent from using Web
Fonts.

00:08:31.729 --> 00:08:38.760
Third, there's CSS maintenance involved. As
the browsers evolve, they support different

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:44.830
font snippets. Just recent -- or font-face
CSS snippets. So just recently, for example,

00:08:44.830 --> 00:08:51.810
IE9 actually changed the requirement for what
it would look for in the CSS snippet. And

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:57.120
it meant that for all the webmasters out there
that have used the bullet-proof syntax, they

00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:02.470
actually had to go back and change how they
used it so that it could work in IE9. And

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:06.630
there is no telling how many times this will
happen again. So there is a bunch of CSS maintenance

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:11.810
involved when you host font files yourself.
Fourth, there is lots of browser quirks. We

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:18.380
all know what browser quirks are. It turns
out that certain Android browsers break when

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:24.280
you source a Web font via the local selector
that we saw in the previous slide.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:28.510
And, also, Chrome Frame is another example.
In certain instances, Web Fonts will simply

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:34.090
not work if you are using the @font-face CSS
rule in Chrome Frame.

00:09:34.090 --> 00:09:38.370
And, finally, there's licensing complexities
involved. Just because you own a font and

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:43.830
can use it on your local machine doesn't necessarily
mean you can use it on the Web. And oftentimes,

00:09:43.830 --> 00:09:49.020
and probably more often than not, the license
to use a font as a Web font is completely

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:54.320
different.
So that's why Google launched Google Web Fonts.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.680
We're, basically, looking to reduce all these
pain points and make Web Fonts ubiquitous.

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:05.200
If you go to Google.com/webfonts you will
be greeted with basically a simple list of

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:10.650
the fonts that we offer.
Today it is 175 open source, free-to-use Web

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:14.890
fonts. And as you browse, you can quickly
discover which ones you would like to use

00:10:14.890 --> 00:10:19.110
on your Web sites and then grab a snippet
of code and embed that in your HTML document.

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:24.530
And I am going to show you in detail how that
works later.

00:10:24.530 --> 00:10:28.740
We've designed a couple other advantages into
Google Web Fonts. So the first thing is that

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:34.990
Google handles the browser quirks. When your
end user goes to your Web site or blog, we're

00:10:34.990 --> 00:10:39.000
going to sniff which browser and platform
they're on and we're going to serve exactly

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.071
the CSS snippet that's required as well as
the font file that's required. And so you,

00:10:44.071 --> 00:10:48.180
basically, don't need to worry about it. You
can have the confidence that the fonts you

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:53.510
select from Google Web Fonts will work on
all browsers going forward.

00:10:53.510 --> 00:10:58.000
Because we do this -- because we do this dynamically,
there is actually a lot of optimizations we

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.710
can have, too. And Raph is going to talk a
little bit about this a little bit later on.

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:06.990
Second, there is no licensing worries because
all the fonts are open source. You never have

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:11.590
to worry about being constrained for how to
use Google Web Fonts. We think this is really

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:14.420
important.
Third, there's lots of speed and reliability.

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:21.880
You're using Google CDN, which is very reliable.
Finally, there's lots of font updates, optimizations

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:28.030
and quality improvements. And the message
here is that as we continue to improve these

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:32.720
fonts and we change it in a central location,
all the integrations just get it for free

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:36.920
with no further work required.
And we're also working on some innovative

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:41.740
font-serving features that we are excited
to share with you today.

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:47.620
So meet some of the family. This is some of
the 175 fonts that we currently offer in Google

00:11:47.620 --> 00:11:53.170
Web Fonts. Now, these don't look like Times
and Arial. Some of them look wild and crazy,

00:11:53.170 --> 00:11:57.360
and that's what we want. We want the Web to
be more expressive and fun and also selectable.

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:03.750
So I encourage you guys to visible google.com/webfonts
and choose some of your favorites, but here's

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:09.600
some of mine. I like Pacifico. This is a designed
by a gentleman named Vernon Adams, who is

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:16.040
a furniture restorer and designer but he is
also a very good font designer.

00:12:16.040 --> 00:12:20.770
Philosopher.
Permanent Marker, which is actually designed

00:12:20.770 --> 00:12:28.820
by a popular font foundry, font diner, which
specializes in high-quality retro fonts.

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:33.700
And Arvo.
You get all of that font selection for, basically,

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:39.290
30 seconds of integration. The first thing
you do is you include this special snippet

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:43.760
in the header of your HTML document.
And in this case, we're requesting the Arvo

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:48.670
font family. The second thing you do -- this
is the easy part -- you just use the font

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:54.220
you would any other font. So in this case,
we're using Arvo to style an H1 element. And

00:12:54.220 --> 00:12:59.640
we are using it right next to Arial and Serif.
It is just that easy. There is no keys involved.

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:06.120
There is no sign-up required. It is just copy
and paste integration.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:09.870
So far we have talked about what Web Fonts
are. We have talked about what Google Web

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:14.720
Fonts is and why Google has entered this space.
But where are we in the adoption curve?

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:20.160
We are really excited about what we're seeing
here. This is our graph since last year at

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:25.200
Google I/O. And the graph looks very promising
to us. We are seeing up and to the left. It

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:29.780
looks like the growth is accelerating. We
think this is very indicative of the latent

00:13:29.780 --> 00:13:34.700
demand from developers, designers like you,
basically who have been constrained to using

00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:38.690
a small set of fonts on your Web pages or
blogs but now all of a sudden the restriction

00:13:38.690 --> 00:13:44.040
is limited. There really is a huge surge of
demand from the Internet and we're really

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:50.730
excited about this.
So today we're happy to announce that last

00:13:50.730 --> 00:13:57.640
week we hit a peak of 110 font requests per
day. And that's across 1.29 million unique

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:03.100
domain names, and we're sustaining about 30%
month-over-month growth.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:08.210
So 1.29 million unique domains is actually
a fairly small slice of the actively developed

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:12.990
Internet. But what's really exciting to us
is the 30% month-over-month growth because

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:17.310
it if it keeps up it seems like Web fonts
are quickly becoming part of mainstream design

00:14:17.310 --> 00:14:22.970
and development practices for the Web.
So who is using Web Fonts? The first thing

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:28.090
is the signs outside are actually using Open
Sans which we are happy to announce is for

00:14:28.090 --> 00:14:33.200
the first time available via Google Web Fonts
today. Open Sans is a great font family. It

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:38.360
has got about 12 variants. I encourage you
to check it out.

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:44.970
The official royal wedding Website uses Google
Web Fonts. The specific way they use Web Fonts

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:50.450
is worthy of paying attention to.
They designed a virtual guest book. They are,

00:14:50.450 --> 00:14:56.140
basically, using a handwriting font called
indy flower. They have allowed users on the

00:14:56.140 --> 00:15:00.090
Web site to basically sign this virtual guest
book in a way they would have signed a physical

00:15:00.090 --> 00:15:04.830
guest book. This is something that's really
exciting to us because it is a new interaction

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:08.800
that would have been very difficult to build
prior to Web Fonts existing.

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:19.310
Mahalo, a popular how-to Web site uses the
font Arvo. Sourceforge uses the popular font

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:23.610
Ubuntu.
And to bring in some holiday cheer, the Norad

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:29.400
Santa tracker uses Mountains of Christmas,
which is obviously a font that's popular around

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:32.490
Christmastime.
But the list goes on and on. It is not just

00:15:32.490 --> 00:15:39.500
large properties that use Google Web Fonts.
It's lawyers' Web sites, small businesses,

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:46.220
schools, builds, startups like JustinTV, Review
Magazine, ZipRealty, lots of Google properties

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:50.530
like Blogger, Google TV and YouTube use Web
Fonts as well. The list goes on and on. The

00:15:50.530 --> 00:15:58.050
long tail is very, very long, and it is as
long as 1.29 million unique domains.

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:01.850
What's next for us? What have we been working
on at Google Web Fonts? Here is where our

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:05.740
three sections are. First we are going to
talk about our plans to add more fonts to

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:09.240
our library. Currently, we have 175 but we
don't want to stop there.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:13.930
And in this section, I'm going to give you
a sneak peek of something we have been working

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:20.060
very hard on which is the new version of google.com/webfonts.
As we add more fonts to the library, it becomes

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:24.910
increasingly important that we do a much better
job of allowing to compare and contrast the

00:16:24.910 --> 00:16:31.160
differences between Web Fonts and truly understand
the fonts that you would like to use in your

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:33.920
applications.
Second, we're going to talk about faster fonts.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:36.850
And, third, we're going to talk about how
we're integrating these fonts into all the

00:16:36.850 --> 00:16:41.010
tools you use.
We're trying to make sure that you -- the

00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:45.280
content creators of the Web have adequate
font selection. We want you to be able to

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:50.250
express yourselves and to build semantic and
efficient pages in applications.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:55.160
We know that if you are in the process of
designing an application for a Web site and

00:16:55.160 --> 00:16:59.720
you don't find exactly the font that you're
looking for, you're going to think twice about

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:03.620
using Web Fonts. You might actually resort
to some of those dirty tactics we talked about

00:17:03.620 --> 00:17:07.250
earlier in the presentation, and we don't
want this to be true. We want you to find

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:12.089
the font you would like to use.
We are relentlessly focused on increasing

00:17:12.089 --> 00:17:19.490
the size of the library that we offer.
We started with 18 one year ago, and we have

00:17:19.490 --> 00:17:27.649
175 font families in the Google font directory.
And we're aiming for 1,000 within 12 months.

00:17:27.649 --> 00:17:31.720
If you follow us on Google -- on Twitter at
Google Fonts, you will, basically, be subscribing

