00:27:12.279 --> 00:27:17.210
application of web fonts -- can be a huge
performance win.

00:27:17.210 --> 00:27:22.389
So we're always looking, how can we make this
faster? I mean, Google is obsessed with speed.

00:27:22.389 --> 00:27:26.299
The faster the pages run, the better the user
experience is, the better conversion rates

00:27:26.299 --> 00:27:29.509
are, so we want to do everything we can to
make that faster.

00:27:29.509 --> 00:27:34.590
And especially for mobile. So I'm going to
talk about that a little bit too today.

00:27:34.590 --> 00:27:40.230
When you look inside of a font, you find that
a little bit more than half of it typically

00:27:40.230 --> 00:27:45.820
is in the glyph shapes, the metrics, what
actually makes the font the font, and almost

00:27:45.820 --> 00:27:51.109
half of it is metadata that's used only for
making Windows rendering better.

00:27:51.109 --> 00:27:54.450
Well, that's really important, and in fact
we've been doing -- in the last year, we've

00:27:54.450 --> 00:27:59.399
been doing a lot of work kind of quietly a
little bit behind the scenes to make Windows

00:27:59.399 --> 00:28:04.389
rendering better quality. So almost all of
our fonts today have high-quality Windows

00:28:04.389 --> 00:28:10.249
metadata to improve that hinting.
But if you're on a mobile device, that's data

00:28:10.249 --> 00:28:13.889
you're transferring over the line that you
really don't need.

00:28:13.889 --> 00:28:20.369
So in February of this year, we rolled out
an optimization that detects when you're on

00:28:20.369 --> 00:28:26.460
a Mac, an Android device, or a iOS device
-- a iPhone or an iPad -- in other words,

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:32.620
a device that doesn't need that extra metadata.
When we detect that, then we serve an optimized

00:28:32.620 --> 00:28:38.879
version of that font on the fly that, in this
case, brings the request down to 29K, which

00:28:38.879 --> 00:28:43.489
is a pretty good improvement.
